T1  - Quotes, Prices, and Estimates in a Laboratory Market
AU  - BLOOMFIELD, ROBERT
Y1  - 1996/12/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1996.tb05226.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1791
EP  - 1808
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1996.tb05226.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This study examines the behavior of laboratory markets in which two uninformed market makers compete to trade with heterogeneously informed investors. The data provide three main results. First, market makers set quotes to protect against adverse selection and to control inventory. Second, when investors are less well-informed, their trades are less reliable measures of their information, and market makers respond to those trades with greater skepticism. Third, errors in market makers' reactions to trades cause the time-series behavior of quotes and prices to depend on the information environment in ways beyond those captured in extant theory.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Determinants of the Maturity of Corporate Debt Issues
AU  - GUEDES, JOSE
AU  - OPLER, TIM
Y1  - 1996/12/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1996.tb05227.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1809
EP  - 1833
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1996.tb05227.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We document the determinants of the term to maturity of 7,369 bonds and notes issued between 1982 and 1993. Our main finding is that large firms with investment grade credit ratings typically borrow at the short end and at the long end and of the maturity spectrum, while firms with speculative grade credit ratings typically borrow in the middle of the maturity spectrum. This pattern is consistent with the theory that risky firms do not issue short-term debt in order to avoid inefficient liquidation, but are screened out of the long-term debt market because of the prospect of risky asset substitution.
ER  - 

